:::summary
Leonhard Euler (1707–1783) was a Swiss mathematician and physicist who made foundational contributions to virtually every branch of mathematics active in his time — calculus, number theory, graph theory, mechanics, optics, and more. He is the most prolific mathematician in history, and his notation still forms the backbone of modern mathematics: $e$, $i$, $\pi$, $f(x)$, $\Sigma$, and more. His identity $e^{i\pi} + 1 = 0$ has been called the most beautiful equation in mathematics.
:::

